The Kogi State government has entered into partnership with the Independent Corrupt Practices and Other Related Offences Commission (ICPC) to combat corruption in the state. This was revealed by the Kogi State commissioner for Information and Communications, Kingsley Fanwo, when he received the state ICPC commissioner, Mr Chile Ogwuegbu (Esq) who led a delegation of ICPC staff on a courtesy call on the commissioner in his office in Kogi. He told the delegation that the Kogi State government under the leadership of Governor Yahaya Bello has done better than any of the previous administrations before it in building internal anti-corruption combat systems to ensure probity and accountability. Fanwo commended the ICPC for devoting attention to preventive rather than enforcement measures against corruption. “Corruption is a terrible sin against humanity and development, and must be fought with dynamism and seriousness. I want to challenge the ICPC to continue to focus on prevention rather than chasing corrupt people who must have wrecked unimaginable havoc on the people. “Governor Yahaya Bello has zero tolerance for corruption and will continue to treat it as a social pandemic that must be fought and defeated for our nation to move forward. “We are ready to collaborate with ICPC in any area that we can to prevent corruption. I can assure you that we will set up our Anti-Corruption and Transparency Unit and also support our staff to attend the Anti-Corruption Academy. “As a government, we are already planning Anti-Corruption Clubs in our schools in order to create a generation that abhors corruption. We must not lose the war against corruption,” he added. Earlier, the ICPC commissioner said the objective of the visit was to seek collaboration with the ministry, being the communication voice of government, and to also urge the state government to set up Anti-Corruption and Transparency Unit in every ministry, agency and parastatal.  